equation_narrative.headline: Lysine emerges from charged context as structural contacts and MLP neurons converge
equation_narrative.story: Position 27 in ubiquitin sits in a charged surface environment with 6 structural contacts. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation that shifts from hydrophobic-leaning (V, L, T dominate the logit lens through L11) to polar/charged character as attention heads read the surrounding context. The representation becomes strongly charged-compatible by L23 (K reaches 70.76%). In the decision phase (L24-33), lysine-specific prediction channels activate decisively: MLP neuron N27:135 contributes +1.455 projection, and high-enrichment SAE features at L30 and L33 lock in the prediction. K reaches 99.62% by L33, with arginine as the only plausible alternative at 0.26%.

perception_phase.summary: Early layers (L1-11) show a hydrophobic-leaning representation: the logit lens projects most strongly to V (peaks at 46.5% at L9), L, and T, reflecting initial processing of local sequence features. Attention heads begin reading structural contacts around L9-18, with 6 residues within 8Å providing context. The representation character shifts dramatically between L17-23: K rises from 5.46% to 70.76% as the model integrates charged surface context. SAE features at L18 show diverse attention-driven signals (F18:6256, F18:5712 with 27.5 and 24.5 projections), indicating the model is assembling a complex biochemical profile. By L23, the representation strongly encodes a charged, surface-exposed position compatible with lysine or arginine.
perception_phase.context_character: By L23, the representation encodes a charged surface position with polar/charged local chemistry. The 6 structural contacts and surrounding sequence (TIENV[K]AKIQD) establish a context where positive charge is strongly favored, with minimal hydrophobic or aromatic character remaining.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within 8Å, read primarily through attention heads at L26-28
Co-evolutionary signal: 1 coupled position detected, suggesting functional constraint
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (61.9 proj), F9:1281 (57.2 proj) encode early structural context
L18 attention features: F18:6256 (27.5 proj), F18:5712 (24.5 proj) refine biochemical character toward charged residues

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between L24-27. At L24, K stands at 70.76% but MLP neurons initially push back (total_answer_proj: -1.5). L25-27 see a decisive shift: MLP neuron N27:135 fires with +1.455 projection specifically for K, and attention head 26:2 contributes +2.415. High-enrichment prediction channels activate at L30 (F30:6302, F30:10092 with 51.9 and 50.5 projections) and L33 (F33:9445 with 134.99 projection). K reaches 91.41% by L29 and 99.62% by L33, with arginine (the only other positive charge) fading to 0.26%.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from perception to decision. At L23, K reaches 70.76% but the representation still encodes general charged character. At L24, MLP neurons show mixed signals (total_answer_proj: -1.5) as the model begins evaluating specific amino acids. By L25, lysine-specific features emerge: MLP neuron N25:4460 contributes +0.608 projection with strong K preference, and the representation transitions from 'charged position' to 'specifically lysine.'

candidates.narrative: Lysine emerges as the clear winner through L24-33. At L27, MLP neuron N27:135 fires with massive +1.455 projection, specifically favoring K over R (0.827) and other residues. L30 attention features (F30:6302, F30:10092) contribute 51.9 and 50.5 projections, encoding lysine-specific prediction channels. The final layer sees F33:9445 (MLP, 134.99 proj) and F33:7034 (MLP, 118.58 proj) lock in the prediction. K rises from 70.76% at L23 to 99.62% at L33.
candidates.key_layers: Dominant from L23, decisive commitment at L27-30
key_evidence: N27:135 (MLP, +1.455 proj) — strongest single neuron vote for K
F33:9445 (MLP, 134.99 proj) — final-layer K commitment feature
Velocity: L27 shows +5.35 total delta toward K, driven by attention (+4.83)

candidates.narrative: Arginine is the only other positive charge and remains the runner-up throughout. It peaks at 18.11% at L15 when the representation encodes general positive charge character, but fades as lysine-specific features activate. By L23, R drops to 6.31%, and by L33 it's at 0.26%. MLP neurons consistently favor K over R: N27:135 gives K +1.455 vs R +0.827, and N21:4842 gives R +0.742 vs K +0.404, but this is insufficient to overcome the broader lysine preference.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L15 (18.11%), fades through L24-33
key_evidence: Peak at L15 reflects charged representation character, not R-specific prediction
N21:4842 (MLP, +0.742 proj to R) — strongest R-supporting neuron, but K still wins overall
Final probability 0.26% shows R is chemically plausible but decisively rejected

candidates.narrative: Threonine dominates the logit lens at L10-11, peaking at 45.91% at L11. This reflects the representation's polar character during mid-perception phase, not a model belief that T is correct. The logit lens projects T strongly because the accumulated features (local sequence, partial structural context) are consistent with small polar residues. As charged context accumulates through L18-23, T fades to 2.01% at L23 and 0.02% at L33. MLP neurons at L10-12 show mixed T signals, but these are context-encoding, not prediction votes.
candidates.key_layers: Logit lens peak at L10-11 (45.91%), collapses by L23
key_evidence: L11 peak reflects polar representation character, not T prediction
N11:1458 (MLP, -0.219 answer_proj) votes for L and Q, erasing K in favor of polar alternatives
Disappears as charged context overrides polar signal at L18-23

candidates.narrative: Glutamine peaks at 16.68% at L13, reflecting the representation's polar/amide character during mid-perception. Like T, this is a logit-lens artifact of accumulated polar features, not a model prediction. Q is chemically similar to K (both have long side chains with polar termini), so the representation projects toward Q when encoding 'long polar side chain' before resolving to 'positive charge.' Q fades to 2.6% by L23 and 0.02% by L33 as lysine-specific features activate.
candidates.key_layers: Logit lens peak at L13 (16.68%), eliminated by L24
key_evidence: N13:83 (MLP, +0.156 answer_proj) votes for Q (0.541 proj) — encodes polar/amide character
Peak reflects 'long polar side chain' representation, not Q-specific prediction
Chemically plausible but lacks positive charge required by context

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from hydrophobic (V, L dominant) to polar (T, Q emerge). The logit lens shows T peaking at 45.91% at L11 and Q at 16.68% at L13, but this reflects the model assembling a polar context representation, not making predictions. MLP neurons show mixed signals: N11:3612 contributes +0.602 for K, while N11:1458 contributes -0.219 (favoring L and Q). Attention heads are reading structural contacts and beginning to encode the charged surface environment.

The representation transitions from polar to charged. K rises from 5.46% at L17 to 70.76% at L23 as the model integrates charged surface context. Attention features at L18 (F18:6256, F18:5712) encode diverse biochemical signals. MLP neurons at L21-23 show net negative answer_proj (-2.08 at L23), indicating the model is still refining the representation rather than committing to K. This is the final perception phase before decision channels activate.

The decisive commitment occurs here. L26 shows +4.53 total delta toward K (attention +1.95, MLP +2.58), driven by attention head 26:2 (+2.415 proj) and MLP neuron N26:2264 (+0.733 proj). L27 delivers the knockout blow: MLP neuron N27:135 fires with +1.455 projection specifically for K, and attention contributes +4.83 delta. K rises from 77.64% at L26 to 87.34% at L27. This is where lysine-specific prediction channels fully activate and the model commits.

deep_dives.label: Attention heads L26-27
deep_dives.caption: L26 head 2 contributes +2.415 projection (structural writer with 98.2% structural attention), and L26 head 15 adds +1.833 (also structural). L27 head 15 erases -1.728 (structural eraser). These heads are reading the 6 structural contacts and integrating charged surface context to support K.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L27
deep_dives.caption: N27:135 is the single strongest K-supporting neuron, contributing +1.455 projection with top votes for K (1.455), R (0.827), and W (0.774). This neuron encodes lysine-specific prediction. N27:4773 adds +0.682 for K. Total MLP contribution at L27: +3.04, the highest positive answer_proj in the decision phase.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L30
deep_dives.caption: F30:6302 (attn, 51.9 proj), F30:10092 (attn, 50.5 proj), and F30:8960 (attn, 48.6 proj) are high-projection attention features encoding lysine-specific prediction channels. These features activate strongly at L30 as the model locks in K, contributing to the rise from 87.34% at L27 to 94.58% at L30.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L33
deep_dives.caption: F33:9445 (MLP, 134.99 proj), F33:7034 (MLP, 118.58 proj), and F33:3601 (MLP, 117.3 proj) are the final-layer commitment features. These extremely high projections (>100) represent the model's final, confident vote for lysine. All are MLP-sourced, showing the MLP stream drives final prediction.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L29-31
deep_dives.caption: L29 shows strong K support: N29:1348 (+0.715), N29:954 (+0.706), N29:832 (+0.684). L30 has net negative answer_proj (-8.2) due to erasers like N30:4863 (-0.847), but K-supporting neurons like N30:3511 (+0.74) maintain momentum. L31 recovers with N31:3170 (+1.069) and N31:2826 (+0.928). This oscillation reflects refinement as the model eliminates alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Velocity events L24-27
deep_dives.caption: L24-25 show negative deltas (-2.81, -3.38) as the model evaluates alternatives. L26-27 show decisive positive deltas (+4.53, +5.35) as lysine-specific features activate. L27's +5.35 delta is attention-driven (+4.83), marking the moment K becomes dominant. This is the transition from evaluation to commitment.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts lysine by assembling a charged surface context through structural attention (6 contacts) and then activating lysine-specific prediction channels in the decision phase. The strongest evidence comes from L27 MLP neuron N27:135 (+1.455 projection) and L30-33 high-enrichment SAE features (F30:6302 at 51.9 proj, F33:9445 at 134.99 proj). The early hydrophobic and polar signals (V, T, Q in the logit lens at L9-13) reflect intermediate representation character, not competing predictions. By L23, the model has encoded the charged surface environment, and L24-33 see lysine-specific features decisively outcompete arginine (the only other positive charge) to reach 99.62% confidence.
